	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Negotiations begin with a ‘road map’</h1>

			
			<h4>
												22 September 2004
										</h4>

					</header>


				<div class="intro">

						<p>The joint SADC configuration-EU ‘road map’ for EPA negotiations begins by reiterating many of the general principles established under the Cotonou agreement with regard to the conduct of EPA negotiations, including the objectives of promoting sustainable development, poverty eradication and gradual integration into the world economy, sequencing with regional integration, WTO compatibility, special and differential treatment etc.</p>

		</div>
		
		
					<p>On the acquis there is a commitment to ‘preserve and improve’ on the current Cotonou and EBA preferences granted to all SADC-configuration countries, in order that all will be better off after the conclusion of the negotiations.</p><p>The importance of involving ‘all relevant stakeholders in the negotiation process’ is reiterated and the ‘road map’ calls for a maximisation of the positive effects of EPAs and a minimisation of adjustment costs, so that any EPA negotiated is economically and socially sustainable.</p><p>The structure for negotiations, which will be conducted at three levels: ministerial; senior official; technical; is set out. Botswana’s minister of trade and industry has been designated to lead the negotiations for SADC at ministerial level, while a chief negotiator will be appointed to lead at senior official level and the EPA unit of the SADC Secretariat will lead at the technical level.</p><p>A SADC-EC regional preparatory task force (RPTF) is to be established to examine ‘the strategic link between EPA negotiations and development cooperation’. According to the ‘road map’ ‘the RPTF shall support the implementation of the provisions of the Cotonou Agreement on the complementarity of trade and economic cooperation and development support’.</p><p>The SADC membership of the RPTF will comprise representatives of the regional and national authorising officers, and relevant experts of the SADC Secretariat and member states. The EC membership will include officials from DG Trade, DG Development, the EuropeAid Cooperation Office and from the EC delegation in Botswana.</p><p>The SADC - EC EPA negotiations will be sequenced in three stages:</p>
<ul>

<li>Stage I: Setting of priorities and preparations for negotiations (July 2004 - December 2004) </li>

<li>Stage II: Substantive negotiations (January 2005 - June 2007) </li>

<li>Stage III: Finalisation (July 2007 - December 2007)</li>

</ul>
<p>The preparatory phase will consist of: a one-week orientation seminar in Brussels; technical meetings between senior officials in November 2004; identification of regional priorities. These may include:</p>
<ul>

<li>support for regional integration; </li>

<li>the establishment of a list of sensitive import sectors; </li>

<li>the introduction of safeguard measures; </li>

<li>the improvement of existing market access to the EC, notably in agriculture and fisheries, rules of origin, SPS measures and technical regulations; </li>

<li>trade in services; </li>

<li>trade-related issues; </li>

<li>legal issues.</li>

</ul>
<p>The substantive phase will consist of discussions on ‘all issues relevant for the SADC-EC EPA’, based on the conclusions of the November 2004 discussions at senior official level. By the end of 2005, a common understanding should have been reached on the broad outlines of the future SADC-EC EPA, and by the end of the stage, an agreement reached on its substance.</p><p>The finalisation phase will be used to enact any necessary legislation to allow the EPA to come into force in January 2008.</p><p>The joint report of the first ministerial meeting acknowledged that ‘the SA-EC Trade and Development Cooperation Agreement had implications on the SADC-EC EPA negotiations and in particular on the BLNS countries’. Reflecting the introductory remarks of minister Jacob D. Nkate, chief SADC coordinator for EPA negotiations and minister of trade and industry for Botswana, the joint report called for:</p>
<ul>

<li>full cumulation between South Africa and other SADC configuration countries under the rules of origin of any EPA; </li>

<li>simplification of the rules of origin; </li>

<li>particular attention to the SPS-related problems arising for small-scale producers; </li>

<li>support to fiscal restructuring. </li>

</ul>
<p>Reflecting remarks by EU Commissioner Hubner the joint report indicated that the ‘EC would like to develop region-specific rules of origin, which would provide for cumulation within the region but also with South Africa and inter-regionally, and take into account the level of development in the region’. Reflecting comments by Commissioner Nielson the joint report suggested that SPS issues could be dealt with on a case-by-case basis.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			

<ul>

<li> 
<a href="http://europa.eu.int/rapid/pressReleasesAction.do?reference=SPEECH/04/355&amp;format=HTML&amp;aged=0&amp;language=EN&amp;guiLanguage=en" target="_self">Speech by Commissioner Nielson (SPEECH/04/355-09/07/2004)</a> </li>

<li> 
<a href="http://www.mmegi.bw/2004/July/Thursday15/757545943658.html" target="_self">Press report (Mmegi Business Week, July 15th 2004)</a> </li>

<li> 
<a href="http://trade-info.cec.eu.int/doclib/docs/2004/july/tradoc_118127.pdf" target="_self">Joint press release</a> </li>

<li> 
<a href="http://trade-info.cec.eu.int/doclib/html/118124.htm" target="_self">Joint report</a> </li>

<li> 
<a href="http://www.epawatch.net/documents/doc160_1.doc" target="_self">Joint ‘road map’</a> </li>

</ul>
		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The question arises as to how the EU is in practice going to improve the trade preferences enjoyed by all SADC configuration countries in the context of the preference erosion which is underway as a result of CAP reform (affecting most prominently the region’s beef and sugar exports) and the conclusion of bilateral deals with regions such as Mercosur (which includes proposals for a 100,000 tonne beef quota and a 1 million tonne ethanol quota), and the introduction of stricter food-safety standards which are increasing the costs of supplying the EU market and could indeed lead to the closure of the EU market to many of the region’s agricultural exports.</p><p>The call for a maximisation of the positive effects of EPAs, and a minimisation of adjustment costs, begs the question as to what specific steps are to be taken in terms of the structuring of an EPA agreement in order to achieve this aim.</p><p>While the joint report acknowledged that the ‘SA - EC Trade and Development Cooperation Agreement had implications on the SADC - EC EPA negotiations and in particular on the BLNS countries’, it gave no indication whatsoever as to how this dimension of the EPA negotiations is to be dealt with. The fear is that eventually the EC will simply invite other SADC configuration countries to sign up to the existing EU-South Africa TDCA, for, as Commissioner Nielson pointed out at the launch of the negotiations ‘an individual state can only be a member of a single trading arrangement with the EC’.</p><p>Given the scale of the challenge facing SADC configuration countries in the light of the EU’s new food-safety policy, dealing with SPS issues on a case-by-case basis as suggested by Commissioner Nielson is scarcely adequate.</p><p>As a plan of action the joint ‘road map’ is pretty featureless, and its priorities constitute little more than a ‘shopping list’ covering most areas. It is an open question whether the formula of a regional preparatory task force will focus attention on the development dimension of EPAs or side-line it, given the different ministerial origins of the SADC participants (finance as opposed to trade ministry). </p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
	</article>

